sec.p:
Regarding social factors, six broad categories (visualized as colored clusters in the diagram,
Figure 1) emerged from the analysis: factors related to food (light grey boxes) or health systems (dark grey boxes) and to individual characteristics (i.e., lifestyle behaviors, gender, education, livelihoods – green boxes) were most often reported, followed by factors related to built environment (black boxes) and to sanitation (white box). Their potential relations to health were analyzed and the most obvious theoretical pathways possibly mediating these effects were inferred from the social epidemiology literature. These pathways were integrated into the diagram as hexagons and their relationships as arrows (plain arrows for direct effects, dashed arrows for indirect effects;
Figure 1). This knowledge thus synthesized can be visualized more easily and may be helpful to inform and guide research in identifying upstream risk factors and eventually providing a way to conceptualize causal processes.

